# Function to extract all labels from the dataset
def get_labels(dataset):
    all_labels = []
    for _, labels in dataset:
        all_labels.append(labels.numpy())
    return np.concatenate(all_labels)
In [6]:
train_labels = get_labels(train_dataset)
val_labels = get_labels(validation_dataset)
test_labels = get_labels(test_dataset)

train, train_count = np.unique(train_labels, return_counts=True)
val, val_count = np.unique(val_labels, return_counts=True)
test, test_count = np.unique(test_labels, return_counts=True)


# Print the distribution
for label, count in zip(train, train_count):
    label = "Normal" if label == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    print(f"Train Class {label}: {count} images ({count/len(train_labels):.2%})")
for label, count in zip(val, val_count):
    label =  "Normal" if label == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    print(f"Validation Class {label}: {count} images ({count/len(val_labels):.2%})")
for label, count in zip(test, test_count):
    label =  "Normal" if label == 0 else "Pneumonia"
    print(f"Test Class {label}: {count} images ({count/len(test_labels):.2%})")

# Define the augmentation layer
data_augmentation_layer = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.2),
        keras.layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
        keras.layers.RandomTranslation(0.1, 0.1),
    ]
)

resnet_model_adam.compile(
    loss="binary_crossentropy",
    optimizer="adam",
    metrics=["accuracy"]
)

callbacks = [
    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
        filepath="/kaggle/working/best_resnet_adam.keras",
        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"
    ),
    
    # Early stopping to prevent overfitting
    EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',
        patience=10,               # Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
        restore_best_weights=True  # Restore model to the best epoch
    ),
    
    # Learning rate reduction when plateauing
    ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,                # Reduce LR by half
        patience=3,                # Wait 5 epochs before reducing
        min_lr=1e-6                # Don't go below this LR
    )
]

plt.title("Confusion Matrix - RESNET with RMSProp Optimizer")

Summary of the Term Project: Pneumonia Detection¶

Training Overview¶

Three Models Were Trained:¶

  • Custom CNN
  • MobileNet
  • ResNet

Each Was Trained With Two Optimizers:¶

  • Adam
  • RMSProp

Each Model's Performance Was Evaluated On:¶

  • Accuracy
  • Classification Report
    • Precision
    • Recall
    • F1-Score
  • Confusion Matrix

Performance Summary Table¶

Model Optimizer Accuracy Precision (Normal) Recall (Normal) Precision (Pneumonia) Recall (Pneumonia) Notes
CNN Adam 85.3% 0.93 0.49 0.84 0.99 Poor recall for Normal class
CNN RMSprop 89.9% 0.94 0.67 0.89 0.98 Better balance
MobileNet Adam 89.6% 0.96 0.64 0.88 0.99 Very high Pneumonia recall
MobileNet RMSprop 86.8% 0.84 0.63 0.88 0.96 Lower on Normal class
ResNet Adam 88.2% 0.87 0.66 0.89 0.96 Balanced but not highest
ResNet RMSprop 87.3% 0.88 0.62 0.87 0.97 Slightly weaker on Normal

Comparison and Insights¶

  • CNN (Adam) showed a high imbalance: excellent at detecting Pneumonia, but poor for Normal cases (Recall: 49%).
  • CNN (RMSProp) improved detection in both classes, reaching 90% accuracy, with more balanced recall (67% Normal, 98% Pneumonia).
  • MobileNet (Adam) delivered excellent overall performance: 90% accuracy, 96% precision on Normal, 99% recall on Pneumonia.
  • MobileNet (RMSProp) was weaker compared to its Adam counterpart (86.8% accuracy).
  • ResNet (Adam & RMSProp) showed stable behavior (87–88% accuracy) but didn't outperform MobileNet (Adam).

Final Model Selection¶

Best Model: MobileNet with Adam Optimizer¶

Reason:

  • Highest precision (0.96 for Normal) and recall (0.99 for Pneumonia)
  • Balanced performance across both classes
  • Highest F1-scores among all models
  • Strong generalization with 90% accuracy

Conclusion¶

The training methodology correctly involved thorough evaluation across models and optimizers. While ResNet showed stability, MobileNet with Adam stood out as the most balanced and strongest model for real-world pneumonia detection tasks based on this dataset.Given the context, MobileNet with Adam was selected because it better minimizes false positives (wrongly diagnosing healthy individuals), which is critical in medical settings.
